<DOC><DOCNO> AP900105-0029 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-01-05-90 0606EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-India-Dam     01-05 0196</FIRST><SECOND>PM-India-Dam,0198</SECOND><HEAD>Government Stops Work on Massive Dam Project</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The government suspended work on a $1.17billion dam project to persuade an environment activist to give upan 11-day-old hunger strike, news reports said.   Sunderlal Bahaguna broke his fast after the government announcedit was stopping construction work on the Tehri Dam, Press Trust ofIndia news agency said Thursday.   There was no indication if the government decision meant thatthe project would be scrapped. However, state-run television saidBahaguna would meet with Environment Minister Maneka Gandhi todiscuss the dam, billed as the largest hydroelectric project insouth Asia.   The dam, 140 miles northeast of New Delhi on the BhagirathiRiver, has been criticized by environmentalists and geologicalexperts who say it is located in an unstable seismic zone and willinundate valuable forest and farmland.   Bahaguna, who has been awarded the Magsaysay award for hisefforts to protect the environment, has been an outspoken critic ofthe project.   The dam is scheduled to be completed in 1996. Its reservoir isexpected to displace 70,000 people, including 30,000 in the town ofTehri, which will be submerged.</TEXT></DOC>